Conceptual Outline for the Analysis of Data

Background

Collecting qualitative data from young children with cancer through interviews could provide invaluable insights due to the extended depth of the information shared. However, obtaining and analyzing such data requires extensive steps like recording, transcription, coding, and manual analysis  all of which are labor-intensive and time-consuming. This poses a significant challenge when working with large datasets or limited resources.

Fortunately, state-of-the-art open-source models for automatic speech recognition (ASR) and large language models (LLMs) capable of performing advanced natural language processing (NLP) tasks now exist. These models can be run entirely locally, on higher-end consumer hardware, enabling the automation of tasks that traditionally required human intervention.

I propose a pipeline that leverages these technologies for fully local, automatic transcription and analysis of qualitative data, significantly reducing the time and effort required while maintaining data privacy and control. This pipeline utilizes OpenAI's Whisper v3 or Meta AI's SeamlessM4T for ASR. Both models are multilingual and have demonstrated transcription accuracy on par with human transcribers. The interview transcripts are then processed using either LLaMA 3.1 8B or Mixtral 8x-7B, as both possess multilingual text processing capabilities. By providing in-context & few-shot learning examples, the models are prompted to perform NLP tasks such as named entity recognition, sentiment analysis, topic modeling, and classification. Finally, the outputs from these models can be analyzed statistically.

 

 

What are SeamlessM4T v2 and Whisper v3?

SeamlessM4T (https://ai.meta.com/blog/seamless-m4t/), developed by Meta, and Whisper (https://github.com/openai/whisper?tab=readme-ov-file#available-models-and-languages), created by OpenAI, are state-of-the-art multilingual transcription and translation models. Both models can be run locally, ensuring that all data processing remains on the user's hardware, safeguarding privacy and meeting data security requirements. By leveraging these tools, interviewers can simply record conversations, leaving the task of transcription to the model. This removes the burden of manual transcription while ensuring that sensitive data remains fully secure, as everything is processed without reliance on external cloud services.

Why dont we use a task-specific model or train our own?

Despite the existence of a wide range of transformer architectures for specific NLP tasks, all models require fine-tuning or calibration to perform well on a specific dataset. This process is resource-intensive, particularly when models are not inherently multilingual.

If we were to fine-tune or calibrate our own model, the requirements in terms of computational power would be significant. Fine-tuning tasks demand high-end GPUs with at least 12GB of VRAM for smaller models, though 16GB or more would be preferred for better performance. For fine-tuning, cost-effective options like the GeForce RTX 3090 (24GB) or RTX A5000 (24GB), priced between 1,000 to 3,000, would be necessary to handle the processing load. In contrast, inference tasks, where the model simply generates outputs based on pre-trained knowledge, require significantly less computational power. Models can typically run on GPUs with 8GB12GB of VRAM or lower-end GPUs when optimized (e.g., using quantization), allowing for more cost-efficient hardware and simpler setups.

The process of fine-tuning also requires large amounts of labeled data, difficult and time-consuming to curate. This becomes even more complex when dealing with young children, as their language is likely less verbose, limiting the available data while increasing the need for it, if we want our model to work across languages.

What is In-context learning and is it really good enough?

In-context learning allows large pre-trained models to adapt to a task by simply providing task-relevant examples as input without requiring extensive fine-tuning or retraining. It bypasses the need for task-specific data and reduces the burden of cross-lingual adaptation, as some LLMs can generalize across languages through prompts and examples, making it more scalable and cost-effective.

What are limitations then?

It has been shown that the models performance on the task depends on the phrasing of the prompt. Thus,  prompt-engineering becomes a relevant topic. Ideally, multiple prompt-versions across multiple languages would be tested to see under which conditions the model performs best.

Exact model performance on our data will be unknown and likely varies across the specific task and language. to validate the models performance a small subset of the data should at least be tested against some human raters.

What is ollama?

Ollama is a user-friendly platform that simplifies running LLMs locally on personal hardware. Unlike traditional Python setups, which require manual installation, model management, and dependency configuration, Ollama offers an intuitive command-line interface and pre-configured environments, significantly reducing setup complexity. It optimizes resource management, making it easier to run models on consumer-grade GPUs while ensuring privacy by keeping all data processing local. Additionally, Ollama supports model quantization, allowing users to reduce the memory footprint and run large models more efficiently on hardware with limited VRAM.

 

Why Llama 3.1 8B or Mixtral 8x-7B?

LLaMA 3.1 8B and Mixtral 8x-7B are particularly well-suited for multilingual tasks. LLaMA 3.1 8B offers support for 8 languages: English, German, French, Italian, Portuguese, Hindi, Spanish, and Thai. Meanwhile, Mixtral 8x-7B supports 5 languages: English, French, German, Spanish, and Italian.

 

 

Overall Mixtral 8x-7B is marginally better than LLaMA 3.1 8B in the MMLU multilingual benchmark. However, LLaMA 3 8B outperforms Mixtral 8x-7B across most other benchmarks, including the MMLU English benchmark.
